"title": "1830&#39;s Barn Beam Chess Set in Wormy Chestnut",
"description": "Beautiful one of a kind hand made Chess set. This  Chess set is made using American Wormy Chestnut reclaimed from beams that were once in a 1830&#39;s Ohio barn. The American Chestnut trees were pretty much wiped out by a blight in the late 1800&#39;s into the early 1900&#39;s. Wood from these nearly extinct trees is very rare and valuable, please Google search &quot; American Chestnut Tree Blight&quot; to read the facinating history of this rare wood. Its really cool to own a piece of history that you know was chopped down and used by one of our Pioneer Forefathers.\r\n\r\nThis set measures 2 3/4&#39;&#39; tall and 16&#39;&#39; square. The side frame of this set is made using American Wormy Chesnut , the top edge  still has the swirl marks from the early steam engine saw that turned the tree trunks into beams and the sides are planed and sanded smooth.\r\n\r\n  The side frame has a beautiful chocolate colored oil finish.   A cool feature of the side frame  is it has bunches of the worm holes from the pin worms that lived in the live trees and gave this wood rare wood its name, Wormy Chestnut .these are visible in first photo. This side frame also has some cool old burled knots, one is shown in the third  photo.\r\n\r\nI try to use sections of beams that have a cool feature from the original post and beam construction.  The first photo has several of these great features. That photo shows a peg hole  which still has the original peg embedded in it.. The Pioneer builder would of carved these pegs buy hand with a draw knife which gives it a kind of stop sign shape, these pegs held the beams together.  That first photo shows a very shallow cut out mortise pocket on the top edge, its pretty shallow so maybe it was for a big hinge or something. You can also see a beautiful burled knot and some tiny worm holes in that first photo.\r\n\r\nThe top is made from planks which are also Wormy Chestnut. . I divide the squares with saw kerfs that are 1/8&#39;&#39; wide and  1/4&#39;&#39; deep, these squares are stained alternating with natural and deep walnut colored stain. This top has a bunch of cool old black nail hole where the iron nail has bled diiscoloration into the wood over many generations and a few worm holes and tracks. I have shown these in the fourth photo.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Chess pieces are imported (from India) wood carved in the traditional French Staunton style. The detail on these is fantastic, the white are Boxwood and the dark ones are Rosewood. The Kings are 3 1/4&#39;&#39; tall with 1 1/4&#39;&#39; diameter base,  the Pawns are 1 1/2&#39;&#39;tall and 1&#39;&#39; diameter with felt on the bottom of all pieces. These pieces come in a draw string pouch with a pamphlet on the rules of chess.\r\n\r\nEach set is marked on the underside the wood species, specific name and history of the \r\nbarn which it came from. Each set is also signed and numbered, zoom in on the photo to see this information.Each set comes with a brochure telling the history of American Wormy Chestnut. This brochure also features photos of the original barn, photo of it coming down, and a photo of the Condos that are now on that site. I have also found and included a copy of a local 1982 newspaper article about this barn and its then owner, Farmer Harold Winston, he mentions its 150 years old at that time. I include a framed photo of the barn taken in the1940&#39;s, it was being used as a saw mill and has giant tree trunks stacked up out front.\r\n\r\nI really enjoy making these beautiful Chess sets. Please click on my &#39;&#39;Feedback&#39;&#39; and you will see previous buyers saying, (and I quote), AWESTRUCK !, LOVE IT, ABSOLUTELY STUNNING, BEAUTIFUL, GREAT SELLER.  Every feedback is 5 stars.\r\n\r\nThis set is a great one of a kind gift for any History Buff, Woodworker, or Barn/Farm lover.\r\n\r\n                                      SURE TO BECOME A FAMILY HEIRLOOM\r\n\r\n                                      SHIPS ANYWHERE IN USA FOR $19.50\r\n\r\n                                           I only ship within the United States",
